Fowler, and Carol Gilligan), and spirituality (influenced by John S. Donne, Emile Griffin, Walter Conn, and Bernard Lonergan). Each text is read in the light of the autobiographical tradition begun by St. Augustine's Confessions, but with a focus on distinctively modern and post-modern transformations of the self-writing genre. The twentieth-century context of religious alienation, social autonomy, identity crises and politics, and the search for social justice is examined in each text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAutobiographyxReligious aspects. 0aSpiritual biographyxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823237456zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823237456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823237456.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK